The paper deals with approximation techniques for \v{C}ech complexes, which are a fundamental concept in computational geometry and topology. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CG (Computational Geometry). The paper also involves algorithms and data structures for computing and representing these complexes, which suggests cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as another likely category. The paper also discusses the use of coresets, which are a common tool in numerical analysis and optimization, indicating cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) as a possible category. The paper also involves a generalization of the known fact that the Rips complex approximates the \v{C}ech complex, which suggests cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) as another possible category. Finally, the paper discusses the link between \v{C}ech complexes and minimum enclosing balls, which suggests cs.SY (Systems and Control) as a possible category.
